{"id":"2303.16907","submitter":"Dan M{\\o}nster","authors":"Sebastian Wallot, Dan M{\\o}nster","title":"Multidimensional Joint Recurrence Quantification Analysis: detecting\n  coupling between time series of different dimensionalities","comments":"Working paper","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.data-an nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  One issue with the analysis of complex systems and the interaction between\nsuch systems is that they are composed of different number of components, or\nsimply the fact that a different number of observables is available for each\nsystem. The challenge is how to analyze the interaction of two systems which\nare not described by the same number of variables. The approach is to combine\ndifferent types and number of time series so that they yield a matched set of\ndata points from which coupling or correlation properties can be estimated.\nHere, we present multidimensional joint recurrence quantification analysis\n(MdJRQA), a recurrence-based technique that allows to analyze coupling\nproperties between multivariate data sets that differ in dimensionality (i.e.,\nnumber of observables) and type of data (such as nominal or interval-scaled,\nfor example). First, we introduce the methods, and then test it on simulated\ndata from linear and nonlinear systems. Finally, we discuss practical issue\nregarding the application of the method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 28 Mar 2023 12:48:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-31"}
